ANALYZING THE CATEGORICAL VARIABLES

Using count plots we can analyse the individual categorical variables with creating a figure with 2 rows and 4 columns

In [111]:
fig,ax =plt.subplots(2,4,figsize=(20,17))
for variables,subplot in zip(categorical,ax.flatten()):
    sns.countplot(x=df[variables],ax=subplot)
for label in subplot.get_xticklabels():
    label.set_rotation(90)

From the above categorical subplots we can analyse that binder,papers,furnishings and accessories that is the 'consumers'and 'corporate' segments are showing more demand and most of them prefer standard class of shipping mode.There is less demand of Technical and appliances compared to other categories

Joint plot gives joint distribution and marginal distribution together using seaborn

In [112]:
with sns.axes_style('white'):
    sns.jointplot(x='Quantity',y='Discount',data=df,kind='kde')

The above plot shows a relation between 'Quantity' and the 'Discount' provided

top15_states=df_Sales_state.head(15)
print(top15_states)
cmap=plt.get_cmap('copper_r')
Labels=top15_states['State']
colors=[cmap(i) for i in np.linspace(0,1,8)]
plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
plt.pie(top15_states['Sales'],autopct='%1.1f%%',colors=colors,shadow=True,labels=Labels)
plt.title('Sales with respect to each State')
plt.show()
